{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17610920","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17610920"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T14:05:43+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T14:05:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16183"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16183","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16183"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8874"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64244"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8874","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8874"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16183"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49676"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"7017"},{"type":"tags","id":"10623"},{"type":"tags","id":"10640"},{"type":"tags","id":"10648"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21134"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21136"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64244","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/64244"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic at 36 weeks\u0027 gestation for routine antenatal care. She has no significant medical history and takes only pregnancy vitamins. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. She reports noticing clear fluid leaking from her breasts over the past few days.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following processes is occurring at this stage of pregnancy?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Lactogenesis I","Lactogenesis II","Galactopoiesis","Mammogenesis","Involution"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient is experiencing normal physiological changes of late pregnancy. \u003Cstrong\u003ELactogenesis I\u003C/strong\u003E occurs during pregnancy (particularly in the second and third trimesters) and involves the development of secretory capacity in the mammary epithelial cells. This stage is characterised by the production of small amounts of colostrum, which may leak from the breasts during late pregnancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELactogenesis II\u003C/strong\u003E refers to the onset of copious milk production and occurs around 30-40 hours after delivery of the placenta. This process is triggered by the rapid drop in progesterone levels following placental delivery, while prolactin levels remain elevated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGalactopoiesis\u003C/strong\u003E refers to the maintenance of established milk production and occurs after lactogenesis II. This process is primarily controlled by prolactin and the removal of milk from the breast.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMammogenesis\u003C/strong\u003E refers to the development and growth of the mammary tissue, which occurs primarily during puberty and early pregnancy, not late pregnancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInvolution\u003C/strong\u003E is the process of mammary gland regression that occurs after weaning when milk production is no longer required.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe stages of lactation are tightly regulated by hormonal changes. During pregnancy, high levels of progesterone, oestrogen, prolactin, and placental lactogen promote mammary development and the initiation of lactogenesis I. The presence of progesterone during pregnancy prevents the onset of copious milk production until after delivery.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Lactogenesis I occurs during pregnancy with development of secretory capacity in mammary tissue.","Lactogenesis II begins around 30-40 hours after delivery with the onset of copious milk production.","The term Lactogenesis III does not exist - milk production maintenance is called galactopoiesis."],"references":["Li S, Wupuer T, Hou R. Factors Influencing Delayed Onset of Lactogenesis: A Scoping Review. Int J Gen Med. 2024 May 21;17:2311-2326. doi: 10.2147/IJGM.S452108. PMID: 38799202; PMCID: PMC11127660.","Pillay J, Davis TJ. Physiology, Lactation. 2023 Jul 17. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 29763156.","Arulkumaran, S., Ledger, W., Denny, L., \u0026 Doumouchtsis, S. (Eds.). (2019). Oxford Textbook of Obstetrics and Gynaecology. Oxford University Press.","Padubidri, V. G., \u0026 Daftary, S. N. (Eds.). (2014). Shaw\u0027s Textbook of Gynecology E-book. Elsevier health sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49676"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16183"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49676","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/49676"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-23T10:29:08+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-23T10:29:54+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8874"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64244"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/23"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd30","name":"Obstetrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67